<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>No. 1153
                    Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State (
                        Dunn
                    )This paper is a manuscript note in
                        pencil which Dunn apparently passed
                        to Byrnes in the course of the
                        Eleventh Plenary Meeting, July 31 (see ante, p. 528), and which Byrnes, with the change described in footnote 2, infra, apparently passed on to Truman with the manuscript notation, “from
                            Dunn”.</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945Berlinv02</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d1153</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">1153</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-07-31T23:59:59-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-31T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="1153" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1153">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> Papers</note>
                <head>No. 1153<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DJC1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dunn</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d1153fn1">This paper is a manuscript note in
                        pencil which <persName corresp="#p_DJC1">Dunn</persName> apparently passed
                        to <persName corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName> in the course of the
                        Eleventh Plenary Meeting, July 31 (see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_528">p. 528</ref>), and which <persName corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName>, with the change described in footnote 2, <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>, apparently passed on to <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> with the manuscript notation, “from
                            <persName corresp="#p_DJC1">Dunn</persName>”.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Potsdam</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-31">July 31,
                            1945</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Would it<note n="2" xml:id="d1153fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName> amended the first sentence by
                        hand to read: “Would it not”.</note> be appropriate for the Polish
                    Government officials to be jointly notified of the decision on the Polish
                    boundary. You might have one representative of each of the three to do it
                    here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJC1">J[<hi rend="smallcaps">ames</hi>] C[<hi rend="smallcaps">lement</hi>] D[<hi rend="smallcaps">unn</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
</TEI>
